Geography & Surface Conditions of Khazadnor

Surface Climate: Mostly cold, rocky, and inhospitable. High, jagged mountains (The Rootspine Range) dominate the landscape. Surface vegetation is sparse — hardy conifers, moss, and lichen. Summers are short, winters are brutal.
Underground: Vast networks of halls, mines, lava forges, underground seas, and crystal caverns. Many areas are still being reclaimed from ancient collapses or demonic corruption.
Major Threats:
Constant underground demonic incursions (especially Grimstone Deep and Grondak).
Surface monsters, bandits, and harsh weather.
Collapsed tunnels and ancient traps from the Golden Age.



Economic Reality Across All Holds
Dwarven economy is heavily militarized and focused on survival.

Strengths: Unmatched craftsmanship, mining wealth (iron, mithral, Aetherite crystals), brewing, and engineering.
Weaknesses:
Constant underground wars drain huge resources.
Low population growth.
Loss of high-level Aetherforge and Rune magic limits production.
Surface trade is dangerous and expensive due to bandits and monsters.

Main Exports: Weapons & armor, masterwork tools, gemstones, runes, high-quality ale, stonework, and golem components.
Main Imports: Food (especially grains and meat), timber, cloth, and luxury goods from humans and elves.
Overall Condition: Most holds are self-sufficient but strained. Karad-Dur, Brimmbarak, and Mithralion are relatively prosperous. The border holds (Grimstone Deep and Grondak) are in a permanent state of war economy — heavily taxed, conscripted, and focused almost entirely on survival.

The dwarves are proud and stubborn. They believe that through endurance and craftsmanship they will eventually reclaim their ancient glory, but the endless war with demons underground is slowly bleeding them dry.
